The '''National Convention Party (NCP)''' is a [[political party]] in [[Gambia]]. It was the main opposition party between 1975 and 1994. It was originally founded on 7 September 1975 when it first launched at [[Busumbala]] by former vice-president [[Sheriff Mustapha Dibba]] two weeks after his expulsion from the [[People's Progressive Party (Gambia)|People's Progressive Party]] (PPP).<ref name="Historical Dictionary of The Gambia2016">{{cite book |last=Perfect |first=David |date= 27 May 2016|title=Historical Dictionary of The Gambia|url=https://books.google.com.my/books?id=9MknDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA306&lpg=PA306&dq=national+convention+party+gambia+busumbala&source=bl&ots=edYGqlVysx&sig=Rc7xxiTXv2iM1J5qkEdUvUTqVEQ&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false |location= |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |page=306-307 |isbn=978-1-442-26526-4 |author-link= }}</ref> It initially welcomed the 1994 coup but was banned from participating in elections in August 1994.<ref name="Historical Dictionary of The Gambia2016" /> Prior to the 1992 elections, the party faced a series of setbacks as many of its leaders rejoin the PPP. Its candidate at the presidential [[elections in Gambia|elections]] of 18 October 2001, Sheriff Dibba, came fourth with 3.77% of the popular vote. At the last legislative [[elections in Gambia|elections]], held on 17 January 2002, the party won no seats. When the party was formed, the then president of the country Dawda Jawara predicted that it would not last more than three months.<ref>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/gm.html Elections in The Gambia], African Elections Database.</ref> The NCP was part of the [[Coalition 2016]] for the [[Gambian presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]], where [[Adama Barrow]] was declared the opposition's candidate and subsequently won.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gainako.com/gambian-opposition-parties-set-select-single-candidate-december-polls-convention/|title=Gambian Opposition Parties Set to Select a Single Candidate for December polls at a Convention|publisher=Ganiako|date=13 October 2016}}</ref>
